I have a h2 startup script that removes WB background pics etc, to
make sure I have as much free memory as possible when starting h2. The
script also included an 'avail flush'. After removing it I can start
h2 a second time without any problems. 

I also found this tip on Dave Myers overclocking page: 
"If you have SCSI lockups, make sure that the decimal value of 
maxtransfer if divided by your blocksize gives an integer result. For 
example, if you are using the default value of 512 bytes for your
blocksize, your maxtransfer value should be 0xfff000. Set this for all
hard drives and partitions on your CSPPC SCSI controller. Note that
that these SCSI lockups can often freeze your entire system, with the
SCSI light permanently on."
The h2 'freezing' I was talking about did leave 'the SCSI light
permanently on' and I have had similar problems with my ShapeShifter
partition. So this might help too. 

