On Mon, 17 Jul 2000, Wolfgang Krause wrote:

> That's nice. Playing a single player game, why is there need to connect a
> client with a server? Could you please explain this any further?

The same  applies for Quake  (and Shogo). The  point is that  there is
always one  entity controlling the flow  of the game,  and a different
one displaying  the stuff. In  a local/single player game,  the server
and client are both located  on the same machine, and the "connection"
is  done via memory  buffers instead  of a  network layer.  The basics
don't change, though, and this gives you complete transparency towards
your programming  model, allowing  the same game  to be played  over a
network as well as on a single machine. 

You could  envision the thing like  a GUI-driven program  with the GUI
being one part that interfaces to the user (a.k.a. the client) and the
program  itself  being  the  part  that  does  the  computations  (the
server). 

However, your problem should really not happen. I would suggest you do
a snoopdos log  and see if there is anything happening  that is out of
the  ordinary. Also,  have you  tried  running on  a completely  clean
system, or  a newly installed one?  Since this problem  does not occur
for  anyone else, it  somehow must  be related  to something  you have
installed... I will have a look  at it again in the source code, maybe
I can find a clue... 

