@node 08246.005
Subject: Re: Dynamic polygon reduction - have we got it backwards?
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <hfrieden@uni-trier.de>
Date: Sun, 30 Jul 2000 21:12:58 +0200 (CEST)

On Sun, 30 Jul 2000, Paul Qureshi wrote:

> goes up. This makes them even slower to draw. Idealy you want to speed
> things up here as well too. How about this: as well as reducing detail
> in the distance why not do it up close too? That way objects in the
> middle distance which is normally where they are look good and close
> ones don't slow things down too much. You could also apply this to
> spline objects like the curved walls in Quake 3, making them get a bit
> chunky up close but otherwise looking nice.

You  can  also   reduce  the  number  of  polies   based  on  relative
movement. For example, when a car  is very close to you but zooms past
at   a   high  speed,   you   are   not   bound  to   recognize   many
details. Likewise, objects that are off  to one side of the screen are
also most likely  not the focus of attention and  are a good candidate
for reduction. 

If  you're  using a  software  renderer, you  might  want  to go  from
perspective correction (even at 16  pixels per span) to linear mapping
if the  relative slope  of the  polygon is very  straigt, i.e.  if the
normal points  mostly towards the  player/viewer. This can  reduce the
per-pixel costs,  but is quite  useless with hardware  rendering (this
can also be detected by looking at the gradients). 

