@node 08246.001
Subject: Dynamic polygon reduction - have we got it backwards?
From: Paul Qureshi <paul.qureshi@btinternet.com>
Date: Sun, 30 Jul 2000 02:14:03 +0100

Hi all.

I was just thinking about dynamic detail reduction as used in many 3D
engines to speed things up. For those not in the know, you basically
reduce the detail of an object (number of polygons, texturing etc) as it
gets further from the screen (and therefore smaller too). This stops you
wasting time doing fine detail on objects in the distance.

However, when objects get close to the screen and very large the detail
goes up. This makes them even slower to draw. Idealy you want to speed
things up here as well too. How about this: as well as reducing detail
in the distance why not do it up close too? That way objects in the
middle distance which is normally where they are look good and close
ones don't slow things down too much. You could also apply this to
spline objects like the curved walls in Quake 3, making them get a bit
chunky up close but otherwise looking nice.

The obvious drawback is the lower quality of graphics when objects are
near, a lot more obvious than when they are far away. However, if
objects moved quick enough I don't think it would be a major problem.
Obviously if noticable detail dissapears (such as car wing mirrors) as
they come close it will look bad, but if you just reduce the detail but
keep something there it should look okay. You could check the objects
relative speed to the camera too to ensure it will be away from the
screen in a few frames. This could help reduce sudden drops in the frame
rate too.

Paul 
